15. seposuit Aug-ustus. This verb is often used by Tacitus of a mild type of exile. Merivale writes (c. 45) : ‘The treatment of exiles seems generally to have been sufficiently mild. They were allowed to a great extent the choice of locality3 and when Augustus forbade them to settle at any spot within 50 miles of the continent, he excepted the pleasant retreats of Cos, Rhodes, and Lesbos. He also confined them to a single ship of 1000 amphorae and two pinnaces for the voyage and conveyance of their famssies, which further were limited to 20 slaves or freedmen.'
